cleveland is balking at celebrating the 20th 
anniversary of the day the cuyahoga river caught fire an event 
which became an unwanted trademark and generated a boatload of jokes 
about the polluted waterway 
imageconscious cleveland officials decided against participating 
in an anniversary ceremony this week during which representatives 
from state industry and citizen groups will cruise down the river 
led by the fireboat that battled the blaze 
dale r finley president of the convention and visitors bureau 
of greater cleveland says he works hard to persuade outoftowners 
to invest their time and money in the area but he still hears 
comments about the river fire 
i just wonder how long do we have to go before we dont have to 
continually bring up that there was a brief fire on a river 20 years 
ago finley said 
i dont read stories about washington dc or from washington 
that constantly mention this was the city where lincoln was shot 
he said 
but to others the june 22 1969 fire is indeed worthy of 
commemoration even though it lasted little more than 20 minutes 
when i heard the river had caught fire my first reaction was 
just disbelief said ben s stefanski ii who as clevelands 
public utilities director in 1969 was responsible for monitoring 
city waterways 
one had never heard of a river burning 
william b sekarek a retired cleveland firefighter who worked 
for 17 years on a fireboat crew said the noon blaze wasnt that 
big a deal 
but i guess it was enough for people to try to make cleveland 
look like a jackass for a little while 
oilsoaked debris was ignited by sparks from a passing train and 
that spread as it burned an oil and gasoline slick the flaming 
section floated along igniting two wooden railroad bridges 
the blaze caused about 50000 in damage but the damage to 
clevelands image was worse as jokes and photos of the fiery river 
circulated throughout the nation 
observers such as robert p wysenski the ohio environmental 
protection agencys expert on the cuyahoga river say the 
100milelong river should no longer be seen with shame 
id say the river is still in a recovering condition but 
theres been a lot of good strides made in the last 20 years he 
said theres been a tremendous amount of money and time that has 
been spent 
the fire forced industries along the river to end decades of 
dumping pollutants into the water and it made neighboring 
communities improve wastewater treatment facilities wysenski said 
and clevelanders approved a 100 million bond issue aimed at 
reducing the rivers pollution an estimated 15 billion in public 
and private money has been poured into environmental improvements 
along the river 
yet the cuyahoga still is listed as one of 42 pollution hotspots 
identified by the international joint commission for the greak lakes 
as needing immediate attention to reduce pollution 
the cuyahoga begins near chardon about 20 miles south of lake 
erie meanders south through farmland and drops sharply west to 
akron before it flows north to lake erie 
